In C/C++ `stdatomic`s on `x86` provides `release`-`acquire` semantic which is free due to x86 memory model. So the point of using `atomic_load_explicit(&amp;i, memory_order_acquire);` and `atomic_store_explicit(&amp;i, 0, memory_order_release);` is that it does not require any memory barrier instruction to ensure correct `release`-`acquire` semantics on x86.

